<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="412" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1663,1688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to 
<collectingRegion box="[671,750,1663,1688]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, the only state where all specimens of this species have been collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="412" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1735,1760]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species 
<taxonomicName authority="Ayala, 2017" authorityName="Ayala" authorityYear="2017" box="[500,664,1736,1760]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jaliscoensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[500,664,1736,1760]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">C. jaliscoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[671,736,1735,1760]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[671,736,1735,1760]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is known from pine and oak forests in the Sierra del Tigre of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,231,1772,1797]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
. It may be present in areas with similar vegetation such as the Sierra de Manantlán, Volcán 
<collectingRegion box="[1312,1399,1772,1797]" country="United States of America" name="Nevada" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Nevado</collectingRegion>
de 
<collectingRegion box="[151,236,1807,1832]" country="Mexico" name="Colima" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Colima</collectingRegion>
, and western part of Transmexican Volcanic Belt (
<figureCitation box="[801,885,1807,1832]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="412" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1844,1869]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Remarks.</emphasis>
Some females present mandibles with blunt and eroded apex. The coloration of scape, pedicel, F1 and F 
<date box="[217,288,1880,1905]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">2 may</date>
be dark in some females; similarly, the females may present reddish integument on mesosoma and metasoma. Some specimens may have almost black middle tibial spurs. T1 with color variation of integument; discal and basal areas reddish brown, elsewhere dark brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
